    {
      "voiceId": "madhusudana",
      "author": "Madhusūdana Sarasvatī",
      "school": "Advaita Vedānta",
      "work": "Gūḍhārtha-dīpikā",
      "locus": "2.66",
      "sanskrit": "imam evārthaṃ vyatireka-mukhena draḍhayati nāstīti | ayuktasyājita-cittasya buddhir ātma-viṣayā śravaṇa-mananākhya-vedānta-vicāra-janyā nāsti notpadyate | tad-buddhy-abhāve na cāyuktasya bhāvanā nididhyāsanātmikā vijātīya-pratyayānantaritasajātīya-pratyaya-pravāha-rūpā | sarvatra naño 'stīty anenānvayaḥ | na cābhāvayata ātmānaṃ śāntiḥ sakāryāvidyā-nivṛtti-rūpā vedānta-vākya-janyā brahmātmaikya-sākṣāt-kṛtiḥ | aśāntasyātma-sākṣātkāra-śūnyasya kutaḥ sukhaṃ mokṣānanda ity arthaḥ ||66||",
      "ourRendering": "This very point He strengthens by way of the negative, by ‘nāsti’. For the unsteadied one, of unconquered mind, the understanding whose object is the Self, born of the Vedānta-inquiry called hearing and reflection, ‘is not’, does not arise. In the absence of that understanding, ‘nor for the unsteadied one is there contemplation’, of the nature of meditation (nididhyāsana), of the form of an unbroken flow of homogeneous cognition uninterrupted by heterogeneous cognition — the construction is with ‘there is not’ throughout. ‘Nor for the non-contemplating one’ of the Self is there ‘peace’, of the form of the cessation of ignorance together with its effect, the direct realization of the unity of Brahman and Self born of the Vedānta-sentences. For the unpeaceful one, void of Self-realization, ‘whence pleasure’, the bliss of liberation — that is the meaning.",
      "source": "data/sources/sanskrit/vedanta/gretil_bhg4comm_ch2.txt (GRETIL: gretil/1_sanskr/2_epic/mbh/ext/bhg4c02u.htm)"
    },
    {
      "voiceId": "sridhara",
      "author": "Śrīdhara Svāmī",
      "school": "Bhakti / Advaita",
      "work": "Subodhinī",
      "locus": "2.66",
      "sanskrit": "indriya-nigrahasya sthita-prajñatā-sādhanatvaṃ vyatireka-mukhenopapādayati nāstīti | ayuktasya avaśī-kṛtendriyasya nāsti buddhiḥ | śāstrācāryopadeśābhyām ātma-viṣayā buddhiḥ prajñaiva notpadyate | kutas tasyāḥ pratiṣṭhā-vārtā | kuta ity atrāha na ceti | na cāyuktasya bhāvanā dhyānam | bhāvanayā hi buddher ātmani pratiṣṭhā bhavati, sā ca ayuktasya yato nāsti | na cābhāvayataḥ ātma-dhyānam akurvataḥ śāntiḥ ātmani cittoparamaḥ | aśāntasya kutaḥ sukham mokṣānanda ity arthaḥ ||66||",
      "ourRendering": "He establishes, by way of the negative, that restraint of the senses is the means to sthita-prajña-hood, by ‘nāsti’. For the unsteadied one, whose senses are unmastered, there is no understanding: the understanding whose object is the Self, the very insight, born of the teaching of scripture and teacher, does not arise. Whence the talk of its standing firm? To ‘whence’ He says ‘na ca’: nor for the unsteadied one is there contemplation, meditation; for it is by contemplation that the understanding’s firmness in the Self comes to be, and that does not exist for the unsteadied one. Nor for the non-contemplating one, who does not do meditation on the Self, is there peace, the ceasing of the mind in the Self. For the unpeaceful one, whence pleasure, the bliss of liberation — that is the meaning.",
      "source": "data/sources/sanskrit/vedanta/gretil_bhg4comm_ch2.txt (GRETIL: gretil/1_sanskr/2_epic/mbh/ext/bhg4c02u.htm)"
    },
    {
      "voiceId": "madhva",
      "author": "Madhva (Ānandatīrtha)",
      "school": "Dvaita Vedānta",
      "work": "Gītā-bhāṣya",
      "locus": "2.66",
      "sanskrit": "prasādābhāve doṣamāhottaraślokābhyām| nahi prasādābhāve yuktiścittanirodhaḥ| ayuktasya ca buddhiḥ – samyag jñānaṃ, nāsti| tadevopapādayati na cāyuktasyeti| śānti muktiḥ| ‘ śāntirmokṣo'tha nirvāṇam ’ ityabhidhānāt",
      "ourRendering": "He states the fault in the absence of serenity by the following two verses. For in the absence of serenity there is no composure, no restraint of the mind; and for the unsteadied one there is no understanding — right knowledge — it ‘is not’. He establishes that very thing by ‘na cāyuktasya’. ‘Peace’ is liberation, by the statement ‘peace, liberation, and nirvāṇa’.",
      "source": "data/sources/sanskrit/vedanta/madhva_gita_bhasya.txt (srimadhvyasa.wordpress.com, Unicode ed. of Madhva's Gītā-bhāṣya)"
    }
